class Solution {
    public void merge(int[] nums1, int m, int[] nums2, int n) {
        int i=m-1;
        int j=n-1;
        int k=m+n-1;
        while(i>=0 && j>=0){
            if(nums1[i]>nums2[j]){
                nums1[k]=nums1[i];
                i--;
            }
            else {
                nums1[k]=nums2[j];
                j--;
            }
            k--;
        }
        while(j>=0){
            nums1[k]=nums2[j];
            j--;
            k--;
        }
        
    }
}

Since both arrays are already sorted, we compare their largest elements from the end to avoid disturbing the existing order.
We keep three pointers: one at the last real element of nums1, one at the last element of nums2, and one at the last position of nums1 
where the merged element should go. At each step, we place the larger element at the end of nums1 and move the corresponding pointer backward
until all elements from nums2 are merged.
